    <question>
        <prompt>The repeal of the Sheppard-Towner Act in 1929 demonstrated:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Growing support for women's healthcare</option>
            <option letter="b">Opposition to federal welfare programs</option>
            <option letter="c">Increased state funding for healthcare</option>
            <option letter="d">Support for medical research</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The repeal of the Sheppard-Towner Maternity and Infancy Protection Act, which had provided federal funding for maternal and child health care, reflected growing conservative opposition to federal welfare programs. Despite the program's success in reducing infant mortality, it was attacked as "socialistic" and ended in 1929, highlighting the resistance to federal involvement in social welfare during the 1920s.</explanation>
